Therefore, it is evident that saving is just one part of it.

Some parents may think that in order to provide valuable knowledge, they must be successful entrepreneurs or economists. This is definitely not the case. We know a lot more about money than meets the eye. Parents have accumulated  a wealth of experience with real life situations, and we are able to analyze and evaluate complex information that we consume in the media. Therefore it is obvious that we know much more about money than we think which we can impart on the children.
Here are 5 useful lessons that we can pass on to our children without special preparation!

Knowing how to spend money is no less important than saving it. This is especially true today when consumerism is so rampant in our society. Store shelves are overflowing with a variety of toys and treats, and it is especially difficult to resist advertising to children. Therefore, feel free to talk to your children about how to spend money wisely. For example, before buying something, compare prices in different stores and online, and suggest to wait for discounts. It is also worth discussing whether the desired item is needed at all! Perhaps it's worth waiting a few days (the 72-hour rule) and if the motivation doesn't wane, you can make the desired purchase. You may also find cheaper alternatives for the desired purchase. I have noticed that children willingly engage in such discussions and enthusiastically find alternatives to their desires without spending money instantly. Therefore, feel free to discuss together and share your experience. Remember, your experience is also a great lesson for children.

Although this area mostly belongs to parents, children can also be given advice on ways they can find opportunities from an early age. The most basic example is earning from a bottle return system or additional work. It is important to teach a child's responsibilities, such as tidying up the toys, making the bed, washing the dishes or doing well in school, but in my opinion, these are not things they should be paid for. However, it is always possible to find additional work for which the agreed remuneration can be paid. With age, work can expand outside the home – to grandparents, neighbours or even more widely in the community. Today, there are many examples of children starting their own businesses capitalising on the internet and earning their first income quite early in life. It is important for parents to support and motivate the children to take up their favorite extra-curricular activities. The lessons they learn through these experiences can be immensely valuable.

Most parents are still hesitant to talk about investing with their children. However, even if you don't invest yourself, you can introduce your child to it and consider together where it would be worthwhile to invest some money. Children will be quite enthusiastic about this topic, because it sounds "cool", and you will have the opportunity to teach them not only about the benefits of investing, but also the associated risk. The higher the desired return on an investment, the higher the risk of losing money from that investment too. And vice versa – the lower the risk, the lower the profits. It is extremely important to thoroughly research the assets in which you want to invest.

A simulation can also be quite beneficial to get an introduction to investing. Additionally, you can set up a savings account where the children put some of their money aside as savings. Depending on how much they will keep without taking or how much they will "invest", allocate interest. Overtime, the process can become more complicated - external circumstances may cause interest rates to increase or decrease. It's just a matter of creativity,  but for the initial perception, such an idea is very useful.

As I mentioned earlier, many children start their familiarity with money from saving. It happens that children are by nature spendthrift and do not succeed in saving. This is where you should offer your help and help the child set a goal for savings – even if it’s a small amount. The ability to set aside part of the money received is an important skill to master at a young age. If the child is not educated on this topic, from the first euro earned, it can become a huge challenge in the future. After all, you wouldn't want your child living paycheck to paycheck as an adult, or worse – drowning in debt or having no financial stability. Studies have shown that financially secure people feel much happier. Thus, saving is a very valuable skill that can lay the foundation for a child's financial well-being as an adult.

Our general desire to share something in a certain sense develops an abundance mindset– i.e. if I have something to share, as a result of it I will feel rich. It's an important psychological state that provides many more benefits than the feeling of lacking when you are short of money. You can donate not only material things, but also your time. In the workshops I organize, children often share their experiences of how together with their parents they send gifts to needy families during Christmas. This is a wonderful example of how to engage children in the sharing process and teach a valuable life lesson. It is also worthwhile encouraging the child to donate unused toys or clothes or even volunteer at an animal shelter to teach kindness. Trust me, the lesson of sharing will be no less valuable than the skill of saving or the ability to earn.

It is evident that you can teach your children about finances more than any school or a special club. The discipline of financial literacy in schools would be extremely useful, however we deal with money every day, and we can learn from simple, everyday situations. This is the foundation!

I hope the ideas presented by me will complement your daily conversations and motivate you to involve children more often in the family's financial processes. If you build on these five key areas when teaching your kids about money, you're sure to develop a much broader understanding of finances amongst them in the long run.

children.value: Why is it Important to Develop Children's Financial Literacy?

Developing children’s financial literacy has become popular because parents recognize it as an important life skill that can be taught from an early age. Many adults themselves struggle with the practicalities of managing money or of growing wealth because they were not taught these skills early enough at home, school or university.

At first glance it seems parents may be unprepared to transfer this type of knowledge to their children. However, necessity is a great teacher. Most adults had to work through their own mistakes and learn the hard way about the real value of money – how to get it, how to spend it and how to save it, as well as how to stay safe and avoid pitfalls. They are keen to share the results of these experiences for the benefit of their children.
Educating kids about money is not only desirable, but also necessary because it is a skill that drastically improves quality of life.
"...it is a skill that drastically improves quality of life."

Most parents believe that children will learn financial literacy at school. Unfortunately, although financial education is taught in some schools in several countries, it still remains limited. In order not to overload the curriculum, educators tend to integrate financial literacy into other subjects and existing courses. Some non-profit organizations and financial institutions try to solve the problem through extracurricular activities and initiatives. But it turns out that children receive basic financial literacy knowledge and skills quite late and rather piecemeal. Schools often lack the necessary specialists in the field, they don’t have the textbooks, and it is not an exam-driven subject and so gets sidelined.
OECD Finds Teenagers Lack Financial Skills

Many teenagers have difficulty understanding money issues, because they lack the basic financial skills. On average, across OECD countries and economies, about 15% of students have no or very low basic financial skills, and only about 10% of students are top performers in financial literacy. This means they can analyze complex financial products and take into account features of financial documents that are significant but not immediately evident, such as transaction costs.

The OECD assessed the financial literacy of around 117,000 15‑year-old students from 20 participating countries and economies – to find out whether they had acquired these skills and are well-prepared to handle their financial affairs.

According to the OECD’s Programme for International Student Assessment (PISA) survey for financial literacy, published in 2020, 45% of 15-year-olds have a payment card or a debit card and 54% have a bank account, but only one in three students (33%) have the necessary skills to manage their bank accounts.

Some 73% of students reported that they had bought something online (either alone or with a family member) during the 12 months prior to the PISA assessment. But only about half of all students felt confident in ensuring the safety of sensitive information when making an electronic payment or using online banking (51%), transferring money (50%) and paying with a mobile device instead of using cash (49%).

The study concluded that parents have the greatest influence on the formation of children's attitudes to financial management. The survey found that an overwhelming 94% of students obtain information about money matters from their parents, and students who do so tend to perform better in financial literacy assessments.
A Great Practical Way to Teach Real Money Habits
Even though parents play a big role in teaching children good money habits, many lack the confidence or knowledge to successfully teach their children how to manage finances properly.

Here’s where mobile banking applications come to the rescue. They can really support the financial education of both children and parents. Such applications help parents illustrate the value of money, while retaining parental control over what their children do with their funds.
Before deciding which application is best to use, it is worth taking into account the presence of such functions as:
opening accounts for children using parents’ smartphones
instant ordering of a payment card for children
instant top up from parents’ smartphones
locking/unlocking the card in case of suspicious transactions
turning on/off internet payments and/or ATM withdrawals

The app should be flexible so that it can adapt to parents and children as children grow up and mature. For example, parents should have the opportunity to switch off all monitoring functions so that the child can start making financial decisions on their own.
It goes without saying that the banking app should provide children with educational tools that will help them learn how to budget and save money for spending goals.
Plus, modern mobile banking apps tend to support child-parent interaction, as common features include tracking the chores a child needs to accomplish before receiving an allowance from parents.

Modern banking applications should take into account these nuances and be able to adapt flexibly to the needs of each particular family.

So, everything depends on our willingness to learn by ourselves and pass this knowledge on to our children.

children.value: Kai paklausiu tėvų, kaip jiems sekasi ugdyti savo vaikų finansinį raštingumą, dažniausiai atsakymai būna apie taupymą. Paprastai pažintis su pinigais ir pirmosios pamokos prasideda būtent nuo šio įgūdžio ugdymo. Ir tai nėra blogai. Pastebėjau, kad daugelis vaikų šiandien puikiai geba susitaupyti savo tikslams ir noriai bei sėkmingai tą daro. Tačiau finansinio raštingumo ugdymas nėra vien apie taupymą. Tai daug platesnė sritis, apimanti ne tik įvairius  pinigų valdymo klausimus, tačiau ir psichologinius (nuostatos, įsitikinimai), ekonominius (kaip išorinės aplinkybės veikia finansinę situaciją), socialinius (kaip mano finansus veikia šeima, draugai, mokykla ir t.t.) aspektus. Todėl apsiriboti vien taupymu tikrai nevertėtų.

Sekantis pastebėjimas, tėvai dažnai save nuvertina finansinio raštingumo srityje ir mano, jog apie pinigus nieko ypatingo negali išmokyti. Tėvams atrodo, kad norint suteikti vertingas žinias, turi būti verslininkas arba ekonomistas. Tačiau taip tikrai nėra. Apie pinigus žinome daug daugiau, nei gali pasirodyti iš pirmo žvilgsnio. Esame sukaupę tam tikrą gyvenimišką patirtį, matę įvairiausių pavyzdžių, gebame analizuoti ir vertinti informaciją, kurią pamatome ar perskaitome žiniasklaidoje. Taigi, apie pinigus žinome kur kas daugiau, nei vaikai.
Štai 5 naudingos pamokos, kurias galime perduoti savo vaikams be specialaus pasiruošimo!

Mokėti išleisti pinigus ne mažiau svarbu, nei juos taupyti. Tai ypač aktualu šiandien, kai vartotojiškumas toks gajus mūsų visuomenėje. Parduotuvių lentynos lūžta nuo įvairiausių žaislų ir skanėstų pasirinkimo, o atsispirti reklamoms vaikams yra ypač sunku. Todėl drąsiai kalbėkite su vaikais apie tai, kaip protingiau galima išleisti pinigus. Pavyzdžiui, prieš perkant kokį nors daiktą, kartu palyginkite kainas skirtingose parduotuvėse ir internete. Pasiūlykite palaukti nuolaidų. Verta diskutuoti ir apie tai, ar apskritai reikia norimo daikto! Galbūt verta palaukti kelias dienas (72 valandų taisyklė) ir jei noras neišblės, galima pirkti. O galbūt norimam pirkiniui rasite pigesnių alternatyvų. Pastebėjau, kad vaikai noriai įsitraukia į tokias diskusijas, bei entuziastingai suranda alternatyvų savo norams neišleisdami pinigų. Drąsiai diskutuokite kartu, dalinkitės savo patirtimi. Patikėkite, vaikams jūsų pavyzdys taip pat yra puiki pamoka!

Nors ši sritis labiau priklauso tėvams, vaikams apie galimybes užsidirbti galima kalbėti jau nuo mažų dienų. Elementariausias pavyzdys - taros pridavimas arba papildomi darbai. Svarbu paminėti, kad už vaiko pareigas, tokias kaip žaislų sutvarkymas, lovos pasiklojimas, indų plovimas ar geras mokymasis, mano supratimu, neturėtų būti mokama. Tačiau visada galima rasti papildomų darbų, už kuriuos bus mokamas sutartas atlygis. Su amžiumi darbai gali plėstis ir už namų ribų - pas senelius, kaimynus ar net plačiau. Šiandien gausu pavyzdžių, kaip vaikai pradeda savo verslus, išnaudoja interneto galimybes ir užsidirba pirmuosius savo pinigus. Svarbu neprimesti savo įsitikinimų, kad neišeis, o palaikyti ir motyvuoti savo atžalas imtis mėgstamos papildomos veiklos. Būsimos pamokos ir žinoma klaidos, yra labai vertinga patirtis.

Kalbėtis apie INVESTAVIMĄ su vaikais, dauguma tėvų vis dar nesiryžta. Tačiau net jei patys neinvestuojate, galite supažindinti vaiką kas tai yra, kartu pasvarstyti, kur vertėtų įdarbinti pinigus. Vaikams ši tema tikrai patiks, nes skamba “kietai”, o jūs turėsite galimybę papasakoti ne vien apie naudą, bet supažindinti ir su rizikomis. Kuo didesnio pelno norima investuojant, tuo tikėtina bus didesnė rizika prarasti pinigus. Ir atvirkščiai - kuo mažesnė rizika, tuo pelnas mažesnis. Itin svarbu nuodugniai pasidomėti sritimi, į kurią norima investuoti.
Supažindinimui su investavimu pradžiai tinka ir simuliacinis pavyzdys. Sukurkite taupomąją sąskaitą, į  kurią vaikai deda dalį savo santaupų. Priklausomai nuo to, kiek išlaikys nepaėmę arba kokį kiekį “investuos”, skirkite palūkanas. Su laiku procesas gali sudėtingėti - atsirasti išorinės aplinkybės, dėl kurių palūkanos didėja arba mažėja. Tai tik kūrybiškumo ir nusiteikimo klausimas. Tačiau pradiniam suvokimui tokia idėja labai pasitarnauja.

Kaip minėjau, daugelis vaikų būtent nuo taupymo pradeda pažintį su pinigais. Būna, kad vaikai iš prigimties yra išlaidūs ir susitaupyti nesiseka. Čia vertėtų pasiūlyti savo pagalbą ir padėti vaikui išsikelti tikslą, kuriam galima susitaupyti. Kad ir labai mažą. Įgūdis atidėti dalį gaunamų pinigų tolimesnei ateičiai ypatingai svarbus. # Keeping Your Money Safe

## myTU is a mobile banking platform that prioritises safety and security when handling customer funds and data

![Keeping Your Money Safe Image](https://cdn.mytu.co/blog/blog-safe-2.jpeg "Keeping Your Money Safe Image")

## The Changing Face of Banking Security
Masked banditos can’t steal your gold because the way people transact and store money has changed. Instead, new security frontiers have appeared, especially over the past decade, including internet privacy, customer ID and digital technologies. All underscored by regulatory compliance requirements.

Smartphones and internet banking have improved accessibility and convenience. Today your bank is in your pocket and the importance of brick and mortar branches has faded, with decreased throughput hastened by the rise of fintechs and Covid-19 lockdowns.

myTU’s money management is designed around technology that provides a 24-hour per day, tap-of-the-finger simplicity, which in the past was usually facilitated by somewhat tedious branch visits.

As new financial trends and technologies develop, the banking industry itself changes, new security challenges appear, and customer expectations change in line with value and an improved experience. However, some things in banking never change – people will always want their money to be safe.

## Trust as Strong as a Vault
Success in any type of business depends largely on trust and this is doubly true when it comes to banking because money is a central part of everyday life. Financial institutions exist to keep money safe as well as accessible. Account holders must be fully confident their money is protected and personal data is handled responsibly and securely.

myTU is a mobile banking platform that takes the safety of customer funds, data and operations extremely seriously, down to the very last detail of privacy and security. We are very proud to note that myTU does not sell its customers’ private information to anyone under any circumstances.

![Keeping Your Money Safe Image](https://cdn.mytu.co/blog/blog-safe.jpeg "Keeping Your Money Safe Image")

## myTU’s App Provides Money Management Safety
myTU’s apps on both iOS and Android are some of the most secure in the financial industry. Customers can manage their funds with complete confidence that both their data and funds are protected.

Authorisation and access to the account are implemented through biometric data, protected asymmetric keys and a secure remote password for access code.

Online and in-store payments are under the protection of industry-leading security technology, including 3D Secure for online, and pin verification for point of sale (POS) card payments.

Moreover, card functions can be easily managed to fit your individual and ever-changing security preferences. All payment card functions can be managed via the interface. You can lock or unlock the card in a few seconds; enable and disable cash withdrawals from ATMs; enable or disable transactions through contactless or magnetic stripe payments; turn internet payments on or off; and set individual transaction limits as needed.

Additionally, customers are notified about all account activity via push notifications.

In short, the app ensures you have peace of mind because you are in total control of what goes in or out of your account at any given moment, backed by the latest in security technology innovation.

![Keeping Your Money Safe Image](https://cdn.mytu.co/blog/blog-safe-3.png "Keeping Your Money Safe Image")

## Remote Onboarding
The apps facilitate remote onboarding and take advantage of security tech that makes onboarding extremely fast. This means no tiresome trips to a banking branch, queues or dealing with bureaucracy that can take hours.

myTU’s digital banking app has one of the fastest and most secure customer onboarding procedures among digital banking platforms, and is available to download via the Google Play Store and the Apple App Store. It allows customers to quickly open an account without being physically present.

![Keeping Your Money Safe Image](https://cdn.mytu.co/blog/blog-safe-4.png "Keeping Your Money Safe Image")

## myTU’s EMI Licence
A key aspect of myTU’s reliability is oversight from the proper regulatory bodies. In this regard you can be confident, because myTU holds an Electronic Money Institution (EMI) licence overseen by the Bank of Lithuania.

In part this is a convenience of geography as we are headquartered in Vilnius. Additionally, it is a matter of fortune, as Lithuania is a leading European jurisdiction for e-money institutions, and a great EMI licencing choice regardless of where you are in Europe.

Our EMI licence is convenient because it supports English-language documentation, direct access to the Single Euros Payment Area (SEPA) through the CENTROlink payments system, as well as the ability to provide regulated financial services under one umbrella throughout the entire European Union (EU) and European Economic Area (EEA).

As well as these benefits, holding an EMI licence also comes with some pretty strict requirements, such as ensuring reliable operating procedures, running on the high-level technology, a competent and trustworthy team, and robust compliance, including strict anti-money laundering/counter-terrorism financing (AML/CTF) and know your customer (KYC) procedures.

## myTU’s Customers Hold Zero Credit Risk
An important distinction for an EMI licence-holder is that all customer funds are ring fenced. All of myTU’s client funds are held separately – most are safeguarded in accounts held with the Bank of Lithuania.

Electronic money issuers like myTU are not authorised to use customer funds for their own needs, so deposits are not loaned out or risked in any way. Hence negligeable credit risk for account holders who deposit their funds at myTU.

![Keeping Your Money Safe Image](https://cdn.mytu.co/blog/blog-safe-5.jpeg "Keeping Your Money Safe Image")

Technology innovation has entirely transformed the banking and financial services industries and continues to do so. Today, access to money with speed and convenience is available to everyone with a smartphone and internet connection.

myTU stands out because we understand there can never be a compromise when it comes to security. Whether it concerns customer funds, rights, data management, onboarding or account access, myTU ensures masked banditos won’t be able to steal your money or your data.

children.value: Kodėl svarbu ugdyti vaikų finansinį raštingumą?

Nors vaikų finansinio raštingumo ugdymo populiarumas ir poreikis auga, dauguma tėvų nesiryžta arba net nesusimąsto, kad šią savybę reikia ugdyti jau nuo mažų dienų. O tie, kurie jaučia poreikį ir atsakomybę mokyti savo vaikus apie pinigus, dažnai nežino, kaip tinkamai tai daryti. Pagrindinė priežastis yra ta, jog mūsų pačių apie pinigus dažnu atveju nemokė nei namie, nei mokykloje, nei universitete. Tačiau edukuoti vaikus apie pinigus ne tik reikia, tai būtina. Štai keletas priežasčių, kodėl svarbu mokyti šio svarbaus įgūdžio.

Su pinigais susiduriame kiekvieną dieną, tad jei norime tvarkos finansuose, gebėjimą elgtis su pinigais svarbu lavinti ir tobulinti nuo mažens. Jei norime pagilinti žinias kurioje nors srityje ar kelti kvalifikaciją, perkame seminarus, kursus, mokymus, skaitome knygas ir pan. Taip ir su finansiniu raštingumu, norint efektyviai tvarkyti savo finansus, šią sritį reikia nuolat tobulinti.
"...mūsų pačių apie pinigus dažnu atveju nemokė nei namie, nei mokykloje, nei universitete"

Dauguma tėvų mano, jog finansinio raštingumo vaikai išmoks mokykloje. Tačiau mūsų švietimo sistemoje tokios disciplinos deja nėra. Finansinis raštingumas dažnu atveju nėra integruotas į pamokas, o jei ir yra, tai vyksta labai fragmentiškai, neformaliojo švietimo būdu ir neturi tęstinumo. Nors ekonomikos pamokų pradedama mokyti nuo 9 ar 10 klasės, tai yra gerokai per vėlu. Taip pat trūksta šios srities specialistų bei atitinkamų vadovėlių.

Lietuvos moksleivių finansinio raštingumo žinios Europos mastu tik vidutinės. 2017 m. EBPO (Ekonominio bendradarbiavimo ir plėtros organizacija) tarptautinio mokinių vertinimo rezultatai parodė, jog mūsų moksleiviai užėmė tik priešpaskutinę vietą. 2020 m. atliktas tas pats tyrimas – Lietuvos moksleiviai užėmė 9 vietą iš 20. Nors rezultatai daug geresni, nei prieš tai buvę, dar yra kur tobulėti.

Nors vaikų finansinio raštingumo ugdymo populiarumas ir poreikis auga, dauguma tėvų nesiryžta arba net nesusimąsto, kad šią savybę reikia ugdyti jau nuo mažų dienų. O tie, kurie jaučia poreikį ir atsakomybę mokyti savo vaikus apie pinigus, dažnai nežino, kaip tinkamai tai daryti. Pagrindinė priežastis yra ta, jog mūsų pačių apie pinigus dažnu atveju nemokė nei namie, nei mokykloje, nei universitete. Tačiau edukuoti vaikus apie pinigus ne tik reikia, tai būtina. Štai keletas priežasčių, kodėl svarbu mokyti šio svarbaus įgūdžio. Su pinigais susiduriame kiekvieną dieną, tad jei norime tvarkos finansuose, gebėjimą elgtis su pinigais svarbu lavinti ir tobulinti nuo mažens. Founding a travel-related business just as Covid-19 strikes is a panic-inducing experience. Many of our big plans became dust when holiday-makers and business travellers exchanged sunshine for the glow of Zoom meetings.

Even the most established companies – airlines, hotels, cruise operators and travel agents suffered; many folded. However, myTU is still here. Our technology buzzes and we already have over 5,000 happy customers at this early stage and are doing rather well. How can this be possible in such difficult market conditions?
"So the expertise is in place, but is it enough when conditions change?"
Founders who are open to adapting
Travel Union was founded by two experts whose vision and skill-sets compliment each other and who are both ready to meet challenges head-on as the situation demands.

TU’s co-founder and CEO is Raman Korneu, a specialist in banking and finance with 20 years of experience in senior roles (CFO and Partner) at international finance companies and banks. He holds a business administration master’s degree from the University of Cambridge.

We also have Tomas Navickas who is CTO and co-founder. He is an IT and technology professional who specialises in building and optimising financial technology solutions. Over the past 22 years Tomas has planned and built large-scale systems, infrastructure and fintech solutions for major banks and financial institutions.
So the expertise is in place, but is it enough when conditions change?
A vision that’s flexible enough to overcome curveballs

TU’s original vision was to create a new digital banking platform – a niche digital bank that connects a wide network of service providers and consumers. More specifically, we wanted to make an innovative banking and payments solution for families and travellers and serve the rapidly growing tourism industry.

However, the travel and tourism industry disappeared entirely just as we were granted an Electronic Money Institution (EMI) license by the Bank of Lithuania and just as our technology was ready to launch.
Did we panic? We consider ourselves to be calm, level-headed professionals, but we did not sleep well.

Luckily TU has a close-knit team and we pulled together to look intently with new eyes at what we were doing. The idea was to create a modern, easy-to-use, secure and, most importantly, money-saving banking platform to make lives easier for travellers and families.

Families are the beautiful bedrock of society and therein was the key to the survival and growth of our business during the initial phases. Global travel was paused temporarily, but family units will always need ways to effectively manage and improve their finances.
"Families are the beautiful bedrock of society."
Banking for you and your family

This is the aspect of the vision we stepped up and concentrated on. Travel Union’s mobile banking platform – myTU – combines mobile banking for travellers with other aspects of daily life, such as managing family finances. And this is the aspect of our business that is currently experiencing the most growth.
myTU is designed for the whole family and was created with the experiences of real parents in mind.

Parents can freely set up as many additional accounts for their children as they want, complete with separate IBAN numbers and the child’s own funky debit card. The process is optimized to be extremely easy and, most importantly, is completely safe.

Travel Union’s mobile app is a great way for children to gain an understanding of money and responsible personal finance, and to take a small step into the adult world, while at the same time having fun. Meanwhile, parents have a worry-free experience because they can make sure the purchases their children make are safe and within budget limitations. Furthermore, a flexible level of autonomy and trust can be granted as long as the parent feels this is appropriate.

The platform offers a solution for parents with busy schedules and makes family finances much easier to manage. myTU’s app is a great lifestyle tool to safely teach children financial literacy and strengthen their independence and self-confidence. myTU also offers many convenient features for adults to save on daily banking expenses.

We are still cautiously optimistic for the future of the travel industry and to be able to focus on this aspect of our business. Summer is approaching in the northern hemisphere and social distancing and vaccines seem to be working as intended. We hope travel restrictions will be lifted soon and that people can enjoy their lives to the fullest extent once again.

TU’s ultimate goal is to become an ecosystem for travellers and travel partners. The ecosystem will unite travel service providers and offer discounts, last-minute or exclusive travel deals and the opportunity to cover costs with our unique #TIME loyalty points.

Users of myTU’s mobile banking app can already enjoy the benefits of having a card that allows payments across the world without paying any commission and earning non-burning and transferable #TIME loyalty points on every card purchase.
As the global situation improves, you can be sure that Travel Union will be at the forefront of doing everything we can to help the travel industry get back on its feet.
Travel Union offers free digital banking and child-friendly financial services in a time of great challenges.

As a fintech startup we are grateful for having the advantages of being in a business that can operate remotely, gain customers and onboard remotely and be able to adapt, and even thrive, in these somewhat harsh market conditions.
We are proud to serve the financial needs of families with children and look forward to further implementing our mission as a family-friendly travel banking platform.

children.value: Saving might seem quite straightforward, except when you are faced with the perennial question – to save or not to save. Children, with the help of their parents can start saving from an early age. It has become evident in many families nowadays. There are still some intricacies associated with saving that are important to know and subsequently, for children to learn too.

We share various connotations about money as adults. As kids, the topic of money barely turned heads. Ultimately, understanding the value of money is critical to also understand the importance of savings. One of the commonly held beliefs is that saving is not fun. For some it stands for missing out on fun activities. This is not true when you consider the benefits in the long run. We can help children form a positive atitude towards the value of money and saving from a young age. So when you communicate with children, try to convey the message that saving is indeed fun. When we save up for something we need, that’s going to lead to happiness. And that’s how savings work – it’s going to eventually lead to a positive outcome.
"So when you communicate with children, try to convey the message that saving is indeed fun."

Another important step in saving is starting from the moment one begins to earn an income. One may often wonder when is the right time to save. While it may be inconvenient for some, now is the best time to save if you haven’t begun efficiently saving already. You have probably heard that it’s important to set aside at least 10% of your income and increase this percentage over time. People usually wait until the time is right to start saving, which in extreme circumstances can lead to dire financial consequences. If the habit of saving is begun early, there’s a good chance it will become a continuous habit with many financial benefits in the long run. Children can be taught from an early age how to effectively set aside money as savings. Like brushing the teeth, it can become a habit that’s going to last a lifetime and be passed down to the next generations. Eventually, they will start saving – not only to achieve any dreams or goals, but to also be financially sound in the future.

In order to spend wisely and save, a crucial step in personal finance management is to divide the money and allocate it to specific areas as soon as you receive your income. This may be for fixed costs like rent, or other expenses like education, charity, entertainment, and also for savings and investment. When money is set aside appropriately, one often avoids the will to spend beyond their means. It also guarantees that they have set aside funds as savings. If parents help their children develop this habit from an early age, there is a high probability that they will learn to manage their finances well as an adult and avoid painful consequences arising from not saving. In this regard, it’s good to maintain different savings accounts for different purposes. To help visualise the goal for children, you can help them label piggy banks with written goals. If the child can’t read yet, a good idea is to draw the goal to aid visualisation.
"To help visualise the goal for children, you can help them label piggy banks with written goals."

It is also beneficial to set savings goals. Saving without a plan can lead to disappointing results or the lack of willingness to continue, especially amongst children. When a goal is instilled, the activity of saving is all the more merrier. It is better to calculate a savings goal for the child so there is a goal to aim towards and effectively save. Even kids who are 3-4 years-old can learn to begin saving for small goals. For example, my 3 year-old son and I have set a savings goal and monitor the progress. I created a savings plan where my son has to draw and colour a coin in a chart when he tosses a coin into the piggy bank. We then hung this chart in a visible place in his room. This visualisation helps him stay on track, monitor progress and desire the positive outcome when the savings goal is achieved. Planning also helps to avoid unnecessary purchases in a store. Everytime the child requests something, I can remind him about the savings goal and how it will be affected if money is spent on gratification now. It has a tremendous success rate as well.
"Everytime the child requests something, I can remind him about the savings goal and how it will be affected if money is spent on gratification now."

Before setting a savings goal with your child, ensure the piggy bank is transparent, in the form of a jar. It is much easier for the child to understand how much has already been saved when they can see it clearly. It also does a lot in terms of motivating them to continue. When setting goals, it’s important to pay attention to the age and maturity of the child. The younger ones should start with smaller goals as they haven’t the patience to pursue a goal for a long period. As the child grows, the saving method can be enhanced. Instead of a glass jar, a personal account might be a decent upgrade. They can create a savings account, set a goal, label it, and start saving. Saving comes with discipline. With the help of some rules, it is possible to enrich the child’s understanding of money and develop useful qualities that lead to higher financial literacy.

children.value: Nuo kada pradėti mokyti apie pinigus?

Vienas dažniausių klausimų, su kuriuo susiduria tėvai, siekiantys mokyti vaikus apie pinigus - nuo kada tikslinga pradėti. Vieno teisingo atsakymo nėra, specialistai turi skirtingą nuomonę šiuo klausimu. Vieni teigia, jog efektyviausia pradėti tuomet, kai vaikas išmoksta skaičiuoti - sudėti, atimti, dauginti ir dalinti. Tuomet jis gali suskaičiuoti grąžą parduotuvėje, įvertinti, kiek pinigų trūksta iki norimo pirkinio. Kiti pataria pradėti tada, kai vaikas paprašo nupirti jam kokį nors daiktą - žaislą ar skanėstą. Turintys vaikų tikriausiai sutiks, jog tai įvyksta gerokai anksčiau, nei išmokstama skaičiuoti.

Yra daug patarimų ir teorijų, tačiau kiekvieno vaiko brandos ir sugebėjimų vertinimas yra labai subtilus. Nors yra tam tikros amžiaus gairės, pagal kurias galima mokyti vaikus skirtingų finansinio raštingumo elementų ir gebėjimų, tikrai neverta griežtai jų laikytis. Prasmingiausia, jei sutelksime dėmesį ne į konkrečias amžiaus ribas, o pradėsime edukaciją apie pinigus šeimoje nuo elementarios komunikacijos.

children.value: When and How to Teach Children About Money?
Early or late - finance is a valuable skill

One of the most common questions asked by parents who wish to teach children about money is “when does it make sense to start?” There is no single correct answer. Specialists have different opinions on the issue. Some argue that it is most effective to start when a child learns to count – to add, subtract, multiply or divide, using coins and purchases as examples. Then they can count the change in a store or estimate how much money needs to be saved for an item. Others advise to start when the child asks to buy something – a toy or candy. Those who have children will probably agree that these kinds of questions come much earlier than learning to count.

Even though there are many tips and theories, assessing the maturity and abilities of each child is a very delicate issue. Although there are certain age guidelines that allow children to be taught different elements and abilities of financial literacy, it is certainly not worth adhering too strictly to them. In the beginning it makes most sense to gently discuss money and finances in simple terms, rather than focus on specific age limits.

Many of us grew up in an environment where talking about money was difficult or taboo, as it was somewhat shameful to admit any level of hardship. Our parents did not talk to us about these topics, and therefore most of us – modern parents – do not even touch this topic with our children. This is because we have no examples from our own childhood.

Another reason we might believe it is not worth teaching children to deal with money is because it is seemingly self-evident and children will sooner or later learn this skill themselves. However, by letting things take their own course, we run the risk of developing inadequate financial behavioural skills. Studies have shown that basic behavioural money skills are formed by the age of seven. They are taken by the child from the environment – parents, grandparents, television and so on. Thus, the risk remains that these skills will not quite fit. Therefore, even a few minutes regularly discussing money with a child will be very useful and help them be introduced to the complicated world of finance.
"A good tactic is to integrate little ping-pong chats into everyday situations."

children.value: A good tactic is to integrate little ping-pong chats into everyday situations. Often we think that a child is still too small and does not understand, but usually they understand much more than we think. While they are still small, we can compare children’s brains with a jungle layout, where everything is scattered and messy. Meanwhile, the mindset of a person is like a city – different objects are connected by roads, everything is streamlined, road traffic is regulated by rules. By talking about everyday situations we transform the jungle in the child's brain into a neat infrastructure and help put things in "drawers". The child starts with understanding the basic principles, and, as time goes on, this knowledge can be deepened.

The most basic things can be taught starting from the age of one or two. Most often children of this age should already have a moneybox. While saving is an adult initiative, and putting coins through a small hole develops fine motor skills rather than financial literacy skills, during this process we can talk about how to fill the piggy bank, shake it, lift it up – feel how heavy it is! This is quite enough to make the whole picture clear to the child little by little. It is already a fun game and an educational introduction to the financial world of the future.

A few years later, when the little one turns 3 or 4, we can talk about where the money comes from, where we spend it, why we can't spend everything we earn, and talk about the value of things. This is achieved not only by talking, but also by simple games, for example, playing shops and shopkeepers. Children of this age can also be gradually involved in shopping planning, setting small savings goals and even sometimes having their own small, separate, shopping budget. And of course, with age, topics should become more complicated and cover as many daily processes as possible. It is very important that we learn how to handle money properly and constantly improve our knowledge of financial literacy, because the most effective way for a child to learn how to manage personal finances is through example. And when we act properly ourselves, it is easier to communicate with children and convey the right pattern of behavior.

Finance is a valuable life skill and children will benefit immensely from developing it. The biggest challenge for parents isn not finding when to teach it, but how? In other words - it is best to find ways to make it an enjoyable activity as well as a useful one. And the author’s humble advice – find your inner child and enjoy playing and learning and teaching just as much as your children.

Kišenpinigiai - bene efektyviausias būdas vaikui mokytis, kaip elgtis su pinigais. Tačiau kaip tai daryti teisingai, žino ne kiekvienas. Tėvams dažnai kyla neaiškumų: nuo kada pradėti, kokią pinigų sumą skirti, kokiais intervalais? Ir apskritai, duoti ar ne? Aš į šį klausimą atsakau - vienareikšmiškai TAIP! Kišenpinigiai yra geriausia praktika išmokti bei įsisavinti elgesio su pinigais momentus, taip pat klysti ir patirti savo poelgių pasekmes. Klaidos, kurias vaikas padarys valdydamas savo pinigus dabar, bus labai naudingos ir padės išvengti rimtų finansinių klaidų suaugus 🤩.

Taigi, jei jau nusprendėte duoti vaikams kišenpinigius (labai tikiuosi, kad taip 😊 ), nuo kokio amžiaus pradėti? Kadangi vaikų branda ir gebėjmai - labai subjektyvus dalykas, patarčiau neturėti griežtų amžiaus rėmų. Svarbiausia, kartu su kišenpinigių atsiradimu, pradėti vaikus mokinti skaičiuoti, supažindinti su kupiūromis bei monetomis (kiek centų sudaro vieną eurą ir pan.), kad jie pradėtų bandyti suskaičiuoti grąžą parduotuvėje ar kiek pinigų reikia norimam daiktui įsigyti.
Dažniausiai tėvai pradeda duoti kišenpinigius, kai vaikas pradeda lankyti mokyklą. Tačiau pradėti reikėtų anksčiau, bet nuo mažesnių sumų.

Juk pradėjus lankyti mokyklą vaiko gyvenime atsiranda daugybė naujų dalykų - kitoks dienos režimas, daugiau savarankiškumo ir atsakomybės. O čia dar duoda pinigų, ir kartais net be jokio paaiškinimo - kaip reikia leisti, skirstyti, planuoti, skaičiuoti ir susilaikyti neišleidus. Jei kišenpinigius pradėsite duoti dar prieš pirmąją klasę, kad ir po 10-20 ct per dieną, vaikas su pinigų valdymo niuansais jau bus susipažinęs ir šis etapas bus kur kas lengvesnis. Tai bus tvirtas pamatas tolimesnėms pamokoms - didesnėms kišenpinigių sumoms ir kaip jas suvaldyti, ilgesniems laiko tarpams tarp gavimų. Svarbu nepamiršti, jog grynųjų pinigų rinkoje sparčiai mažėja, daugelyje vietų atsiskaitymas vyksta kortelėmis, daug ką perkame internetu, net mokyklos valgykloje greitu metu bus galima atsiskaityti tik kortele. Neišvengiamai korteles privalės turėti ir vaikai, tad paruošiamasis etapas yra labai svarbus.

Su laiku didinkite intervalą - pvz, jei iš pradžių duosite kasdien, po kurio laiko galima pradėti duoti po kelis arba vieną kartą per savaitę (pvz., pirmadieniais ir trečiadieniais, vėliau tik pirmadieniais, dar vėliau 1 ir 15 mėnesio dieną) - taip vaikas išmoks planuoti. children.value: The most important aspects of giving pocket money. Part 1

Pocket money is probably the most effective way for a child to learn how to deal with money at a young age. However, not everyone knows how to do it correctly. Parents are often confused; when should I start? How much money should I allocate? How regularly should I give it? And in general, to give or not to give? Unequivocally, YES! Pocket money is the best way for a child to learn and master how to deal with money. It allows them to be smart with money, make mistakes and learn from them. The mistakes a child makes in managing their money now will be nothing compared to the serious financial repercussions they may face as an adult when they haven’t learned the art early 🧐.

So, if you've already decided to give your kids pocket money (I really hope so 😊), at what age should you start? Since children's maturity and abilities are subjective, I would advise not to have strict age limits. The most important thing is to start teaching children how to count money properly by introducing notes and coins (for example, how many cents make up one euro, etc.). This way, they start calculating the change they received in the store or how much money they need to buy a desired item.
Parents usually start giving pocket money when their child starts going to school. Interestingly, you can start much earlier than that, but with smaller amounts of money.

Parents usually start giving pocket money when their child starts going to school. Interestingly, you can start much earlier than that, but with smaller amounts of money. After all, starting to attend school changes many aspects of a child's life – a different daily routine, more independence and a sense of responsibility. On top of that, parents start giving pocket money, and sometimes even without any explanation - how to spend, distribute, plan, calculate and refrain from spending. If you start giving pocket money before the first grade, even just 10-20 cents a day, the child will already be familiar with the subtle nuances of money management even before school. This will be a solid foundation for further lessons – larger amounts of pocket money and how to manage it with longer intervals between receipts by the child. It is important to remember that the world is becoming more and more cashless and we buy a lot of products online now than before, therefore, even in the school canteen it might soon be possible to pay only by card. Inevitably, children will also have to keep a card on hand, so early preparation is beneficial.

"It is important to remember that the world is becoming more and more cashless and we buy a lot of products online now than before, therefore, even in the school canteen it might soon be possible to pay only by card."

Timing is one of the key aspects of giving pocket money. If it is not followed regularly, it will be difficult to assess the benefits of pocket money. When giving your child pocket money, do it at regular intervals. Then lengthen the interval over time – for example, if you gave it daily at first, after a while you can start giving it only a few times or just once a week (for example, on Mondays and Wednesdays, then only on Mondays. As the child gets the hang of managing their pocket money, you can lengthen the interval even further for example, on the 1st and 15th days of the of the month. This way the child learns to plan and spend. After all, we get paid on time, and delays can be distressing.

There is a good chance that on the first few occasions the child will spend several days' pocket money in an instant. And that's probably the best thing that could happen! Why? Because this experience will be enormously valuable and will help them avoid more serious financial mistakes in the future. It’s better to make small mistakes now than big financial mistakes in the future. It is much better to lose 5 euros when you are 7 than to spend a whole month's salary in the first few days even before paying utility bills and rent when they are 20 years-old. It might be hard to fathom now that your child might make such mistakes in the future, but the truth is that even amongst ourselves we have carelessly spent on so many occasions and wished we planned that better. In my experience, I constantly hear stories of children who have started living independently who do not understand many basic things about managing finances. This is not because they are careless. Young people simply lack the knowledge of financial literacy and basic communication with parents on the subject of money.
So, if your child spends his daily allowance ahead of time, do not rush to "rescue" him.

So, if your child spends his daily allowance ahead of time, do not rush to "rescue" him. Let him feel the consequences of his action. If there is no money left for lunch at school, look at it creatively – offer to pack something from home 🤩. Most importantly, do not become exasperated, discuss this event with the children instead. Share similar stories from your life. Also, together make a list of the child's essential expenses to help them understand how to plan and spend.

I hope that the main aspects of pocket money have become much easier to understand and that you will easily apply them in your daily life. Educate your children on the importance of sound financial literacy. They will definitely thank you in the future!

children.value: Taupymas iš pirmo žvilgsnio atrodo paprastas ir aiškus procesas, dėl kurio neturėtų kilti papildomų klausimų - tiesiog taupai arba ne. Dažniausiai vaikai, tėvelių padedami, pradeda taupyti nuo mažų dienų. Šis procesas daugelyje šeimų tapo savaime suprantamas ir reikalingas. Tačiau yra keletas niuansų, į kuriuos svarbu atkreipti dėmesį ir įsisąmoninti, o dar geriau - perduoti savo vaikams.

Labai dažnai pinigų temą lydi įsitikinimai. Juos atsinešame iš vaikystės, kuomet apie pinigus buvo labai minimaliai arba iš vis nekalbama. Vyravo įvairūs posakiai ir nuostatos, o tai padarė įtaką daugelio iš mūsų santykiui bei elgsenai su pinigais. Kalbant apie taupymą, vienas dažniausių klaidingų įsitikinimų yra tas, jog taupyti yra nesmagu. Taupant pinigus, tenka atsisakyti malonumų. Todėl šis veiksmas iš pirmo žvilgsnio gali pasirodyti neįdomus ir atstumiantis. Bet mes galime padėti vaikams suformuoti daug teigiamesnį požiūrį į šį procesą. Kalbėdami su vaikais, stenkitės perteikti nuostatą, kad taupyti yra smagu. Kai susitaupome norimam pirkiniui, esame laimingi. Štai tokį rezultatą duoda taupymas. Todėl tai iš tiesų nuostabus ir vertingas procesas.
"Kalbėdami su vaikais, stenkitės perteikti nuostatą, kad taupyti yra smagu."

Dar vienas labai svarbus taupymo niuansas - atsidėti būtina nuo pirmo uždirbto euro! Tikriausiai ne kartą esate girdėję, kad svarbu atsidėti bent 10 proc. nuo savo uždirbtų pajamų ir su laiku šį procentą didinti. Bėda ta, jog didelė dalis žmonių su šiuo įpročiu turi problemą. Jiems sunku atsidėti arba šį įprotį išsiugdo gerokai per vėlai, dažniausiai patyrę skaudžias finansines pasekmes. Jei įprotis atsidėti bus ugdomas nuo pirmųjų uždirbtų pinigų, labai didelė tikimybė, jog jis taps tvirtas ir vaikas suaugęs tai darys nuolat. Taip kaip asmeninė higiena, kaip dantų valymas ar prausimasis. Ugdant nuo mažų dienų, įprotis atsidėti dalį gaunamų pinigų taps savaime suprantamu dalyku. Tad labai svarbu kalbėti apie tai, kai vaikas pradeda gauti arba užsidirbti pirmuosius pinigus, paskatinti atsidėti dalį ilgalaikiam taupymui, ne tik svajonėms ir tikslams.

Savo pinigus reikia skirstyti. Remiantis asmeninių finansų valdymo taisyklėmis, mes turime skirstyti savo pajamas, kai tik jas gauname (būtinosioms išlaidoms, taupymui bei investavimui, pramogoms, edukacijai, aukojimui). Jei nuo mažens padėsime vaikui išsiugdyti šį įprotį, labai didelė tikimybė, jog suaugęs jis puikiai valdys savo finansus ir išvengs skaudžių finansinių klaidų. Įprasti skirstyti savo pajamas gali padėti skirtingos taupyklės skirtingiems tikslams. Labai pagelbėja tikslų vizualizavimas - ant taupyklių klijuokite etiketes su užrašytais tikslais arba juos nupieškite, jei vaikas dar nemoka skaityti.
"Labai pagelbėja tikslų vizualizavimas - ant taupyklių klijuokite etiketes su užrašytais tikslais arba juos nupieškite"

Labai sveika ir naudinga išsikelti taupymo tikslus. Būna, jog vaikai pinigus taupo be tikslo. Arba keliems norams. Dažniausiai tai daro be jokio plano ir skaičiavimų. Tačiau verta pasiūlyti vaikui iš anksto išsikelti taupymo tikslus ir juos atskirti. Tokios savybės, kaip gebėjimas išsikelti tikslus ir jų siekti yra labai naudingos ir vertinamos. Jų ugdymas nuo mažens vienareikšmiškai atneša naudos.  Pradėti galima net ir labai anksti, nuo 3-4 metų. Štai pavyzdžiui mes su 3,5 metų sūnumi išsikėlėme tikslą, kam taupysime. Padariau vizualų taupymo planą, kuriame sūnus nuspalvina monetas, kurias tuo metu meta į taupyklę. Pavaizduotas noras (mašinėlių trasa) nuolat apie save primindavo. Kabėdamas matomoje kambario vietoje, planas padėjo vaikui suvokti, kiek jau sutaupyta ir kiek liko iki tikslo. Tai skatino  pagalvoti, iš kur galėtume gauti pinigų (aišku su mano pagalba), galbūt priduoti tarą. Toks planavimas taip pat padeda išvengti nereikalingų pirkinių ir prašymų parduotuvėje. Kaskart vaikui pradėjus prašyti, primenu apie mūsų tikslą - jei dabar išleisime pinigus skanėstams, trasos teks laukti ilgiau. Dažnu atveju tai veikia.
"Kaskart vaikui pradėjus prašyti, primenu apie mūsų tikslą - jei dabar išleisime pinigus skanėstams, trasos teks laukti ilgiau."

Prieš keliant su vaiku taupymo tikslus, pasirūpinkite, kad taupyklė būtų permatoma. Tam puikiai tinka stiklainiai. Vaikui daug lengviau suvokti, kiek jau sutaupyta, kai jis tai mato vizualiai. Taip pat tai didina motyvaciją nesustoti.
Svarbu atkreipti dėmesį į vaiko amžių ir brandą. Kuo jaunesnis amžius, tuo tikslas turėtų būti mažesnis, nes maži vaikai gali pritrūkti kantrybės ilgai siekti tikslo.

Kaip jau supratote, taupymas nėra tiesiog paprastas procesas. Pasitelkus tam tikrus niuansus, galima praturtinti vaiko suvokimą apie pinigus, padėti išsiugdyti nuostabias savybes ir žinoma, auginti finansinio raštingumo kompetenciją. O vaikui augant, tiesiog keisti taupymo formatą. Vietoje skaidraus stiklainio turėtų atsirasti asmeninė sąskaita, kurioje yra galimybė susikurti taupomąją sąskaitą ir dalį gaunamų pinigų atidėti ten.

Tikriausiai ne kartą esate girdėję, kad svarbu atsidėti bent 10 proc. nuo savo uždirbtų pajamų ir su laiku šį procentą didinti. Bėda ta, jog didelė dalis žmonių su šiuo įpročiu turi problemą. Jiems sunku atsidėti arba šį įprotį išsiugdo gerokai per vėlai, dažniausiai patyrę skaudžias finansines pasekmes. Jei įprotis atsidėti bus ugdomas nuo pirmųjų uždirbtų pinigų, labai didelė tikimybė, jog jis taps tvirtas ir vaikas suaugęs tai darys nuolat. Taip kaip asmeninė higiena, kaip dantų valymas ar prausimasis. Ugdant nuo mažų dienų, įprotis atsidėti dalį gaunamų pinigų taps savaime suprantamu dalyku. Tad labai svarbu kalbėti apie tai, kai vaikas pradeda gauti arba užsidirbti pirmuosius pinigus, paskatinti atsidėti dalį ilgalaikiam taupymui, ne tik svajonėms ir tikslams. Savo pinigus reikia skirstyti. Remiantis asmeninių finansų valdymo taisyklėmis, mes turime skirstyti savo pajamas, kai tik jas gauname (būtinosioms išlaidoms, taupymui bei investavimui, pramogoms, edukacijai, aukojimui). Jei nuo mažens padėsime vaikui išsiugdyti šį įprotį, labai didelė tikimybė, jog suaugęs jis puikiai valdys savo finansus ir išvengs skaudžių finansinių klaidų. Įprasti skirstyti savo pajamas gali padėti skirtingos taupyklės skirtingiems tikslams. Labai pagelbėja tikslų vizualizavimas - ant taupyklių klijuokite etiketes su užrašytais tikslais arba juos nupieškite, jei vaikas dar nemoka skaityti.  ![Taupykles](https://cdn.mytu.co/blog/lt/blog-saving-father-daughter.jpg "Skirtingos taupyklės - skirtingiems tikslams") > "Labai pagelbėja tikslų vizualizavimas - ant taupyklių klijuokite etiketes su užrašytais tikslais arba juos nupieškite" Labai sveika ir naudinga išsikelti taupymo tikslus. Būna, jog vaikai pinigus taupo be tikslo. Arba keliems norams. Dažniausiai tai daro be jokio plano ir skaičiavimų. Tačiau verta pasiūlyti vaikui iš anksto išsikelti taupymo tikslus ir juos atskirti. Tokios savybės, kaip gebėjimas išsikelti tikslus ir jų siekti yra labai naudingos ir vertinamos. Jų ugdymas nuo mažens vienareikšmiškai atneša naudos. Pradėti galima net ir labai anksti, nuo 3-4 metų. Štai pavyzdžiui mes su 3,5 metų sūnumi išsikėlėme tikslą, kam taupysime. Padariau vizualų taupymo planą, kuriame sūnus nuspalvina monetas, kurias tuo metu meta į taupyklę. Pavaizduotas noras (mašinėlių trasa) nuolat apie save primindavo. Kabėdamas matomoje kambario vietoje, planas padėjo vaikui suvokti, kiek jau sutaupyta ir kiek liko iki tikslo. Tai skatino pagalvoti, iš kur galėtume gauti pinigų (aišku su mano pagalba), galbūt priduoti tarą. Toks planavimas taip pat padeda išvengti nereikalingų pirkinių ir prašymų parduotuvėje. Kaskart vaikui pradėjus prašyti, primenu apie mūsų tikslą - jei dabar išleisime pinigus skanėstams, trasos teks laukti ilgiau. Dažnu atveju tai veikia. ![TaupymoPlanas](https://cdn.mytu.co/blog/lt/blog-saving-steps-plan.png "Domo taupymo planas") > "Kaskart vaikui pradėjus prašyti, primenu apie mūsų tikslą - jei dabar išleisime pinigus skanėstams, trasos teks laukti ilgiau." Prieš keliant su vaiku taupymo tikslus, pasirūpinkite, kad taupyklė būtų permatoma. Tam puikiai tinka stiklainiai. Vaikui daug lengviau suvokti, kiek jau sutaupyta, kai jis tai mato vizualiai. Taip pat tai didina motyvaciją nesustoti. Svarbu atkreipti dėmesį į vaiko amžių ir brandą. Kuo jaunesnis amžius, tuo tikslas turėtų būti mažesnis, nes maži vaikai gali pritrūkti kantrybės ilgai siekti tikslo. Kaip jau supratote, taupymas nėra tiesiog paprastas procesas. Pasitelkus tam tikrus niuansus, galima praturtinti vaiko suvokimą apie pinigus, padėti išsiugdyti nuostabias savybes ir žinoma, auginti finansinio raštingumo kompetenciją. O vaikui augant, tiesiog keisti taupymo formatą. Vietoje skaidraus stiklainio turėtų atsirasti asmeninė sąskaita, kurioje yra galimybė susikurti taupomąją sąskaitą ir dalį gaunamų pinigų atidėti ten.

Responsible for managing the department’s everyday work, improving job procedures/work processes and ensuring cooperation with other structural units within area of Department’s activity, describing and implementing compliance best practices.

## Head of AML will take care of:
- business partnership and leadership on all AML/CTF and international sanctions compliance matters;
- providing timely and accurate advice in support of the business strategy;
- review of all significant business activities for potential AML/CTF and international sanctions compliance risk and required mitigation measures;
- design and implementation of remediation plans and activities to correct any locally identified breakdown in  AML/CTF and international sanctions compliance control; preparedness and coordination to meet and report on  AML/CTF and international sanctions compliance with the requirements of local and international regulators in respect of aspects of our operations;

- liaising with external stakeholders such as competent authorities, Lithuania’s and EU institutions, agencies and bodies regarding AML/CTF and international sanctions compliance issues ;

# Teisininkas (-ė) / Vyresnysis teisininkas (-ė) (įmonių ir finansinių paslaugų teisė)

## Jei:
- turi patirties banke, FinTech, finansinių paslaugų sektoriuje, įmonių teisėje
- esi kvalifikuotas teisininkas, turintis 4-7 m. patirtį
- esi pasirengęs spręsti klausimus savarankiškai ir komandoje
- turi gerą supratimą apie finansinių paslaugų reguliavimo lauką ir paslaugas
- gebi teikti gaires ir rekomendacijas dėl taisomųjų veiksmų ar rizikos mažinimo strategijų ir užtikrinti tinkamą jų įgyvendinimą
- pasižymi proaktyvumu ir stipriomis kiekybinės/kokybinės analizės savybėmis
- aukšti etikos standartai tau yra kasdienybė

## Ką reikės daryti?
- teikti teisinius  patarimus, struktūrizuojant ir konsultuojant organizacijos darbuotojus, įskaitant dalyvavimą rengiant atitinkamus reguliuojamo subjekto dokumentus, derybas su partneriais ir paslaugų teikėjais
- rengti sutartis
- bendrauti ir sąveikauti su kitais departamentais, teikiant jiems teisinę pagalbą
- stebėti reguliavimo pokyčius bei juos įgyvendinti

## Ką mes turime/siūlome:
- pagrįstą verslo modelį ir profesionalų komandą. Jokios aukštos rizikos ir nesuprantamų veiklų
- pažangias IT sistemas  ir FinTech dvasią atitinkančią dinamiką
- pasidalinimą įžvalgomis, patirtimi ir žiniomis bei visapusišką paramą
- šiandienines rinkos sąlygas atitinkantį atlygį, opcionų programą, tęstinių, apmokamų mokymų programą
- suteiksim visus įrankius ir lankstumą tam, kad taptum geriausia savo paties versija ir atliktum reikšmingą vaidmenį organizacijoje

**Darbo užmokestis priklausomai nuo kvalifikacijos:** 5,000-7,000 euro (brutto)


Siųskite savo CV: [cv@travelunion.eu](mailto:cv@travelunion.eu)

Siųsdami savo CV, sutinkate su UAB "Travel Union" [Kandidatų Privatumo Politika](https://mytu.lt/teisine-informacija?document=CP).

# Sukčiavimo ir AML rizikų (monitoring) ekspertas/projektų vadovas(-ė), kuriai(m) įdomu:

- būti proceso (finansinių nusikaltimų prevencijos, transakcijų stebėsenos) šeimininke(u)
- paprastinti, skaitmeninti, optimizuoti ir tobulinti procesus
- mokėjimo sukčiavimų bei kitų sukčiavimų atvejų identifikavimas, vidinių tyrimų atlikimas
- transakcijų tikrinimas ir monitoringas
- atlikti ne tik rutinines, bet ir sudėtingas užduotis

## Ką mes turime/siūlome:
- dinamišką ir įdomų darbo pobūdį, bei aplinką kurioje gali greitai augti. Nuo finansinių nusikaltimų sistemų kūrimo, veiklos modelių ir procesų kūrimo iki analitinių metodų, pagrįstų didžiaisiais duomenimis, vystymo ir nustatymo;
- pagrįstą verslo modelį ir profesionalų komandą, galimybę daryti svarbią įtaką visai organizacijai. Jokios aukštos rizikos ir iki galo nesuprantamų veiklų;
- pažangias IT sistemas - automatinius AML/CTF scoringą ir onboardingą (jei nėra high risk faktorių), integruotą monitoring platformą real time klientų bei transakcijų screeninimui, bei automatinį transakcijų monitoringą;
- Šiandienines rinkos sąlygas atitinkantį atlygį, opcionų programą, mokymų programą;
- DUK, priklausomai nuo kvalifacijos, 2500-4000 EUR/mėn. (brutto).

## Jei:
- turi 2-3 m. Monitoring/AML officer patirties finansų įstaigoje (privalumas Fintech, FSI)
- turi aukštąjį išsilavinimą
- pasižymi proaktyvumu, analitinėmis savybėmis (atidumas detalėms)
- laisvai kalbi anglų kalba (lenkų, ispanų, vokiečių, kalba būtų privalumas)
- esi smalsus(-i) ir drąsus(-i) klausti nepatogių klausimų

# Security Officer

## About Us
Travel Union is a digital banking platform offering payment and loyalty solutions for private consumers (with a focus on families with children) and businesses. We currently operate under an e-money license provided by the Bank of Lithuania. The license can also be used across the European Economic Area (EEA). In January 2021 Travel Union was granted Mastercard Affiliate license.

Travel Union’s integrated offering includes: myTU mobile banking app, online banking and payment system for businesses and a unified loyalty program.

Our team is expanding and we’re looking for a Security Officer. If you’re interested, APPLY now! [cv@travelunion.eu](mailto:cv@travelunion.eu).

## Required knowledge and skills:
- PCI DSS standard
- Secure coding
- Application development life cycle
- IT security (cloud)

## Your tasks will involve:
- preparing processes and documents to maintain/execute PCI DSS certifications
- choosing PCI DSS auditors, negotiating, executing audit
- day-to-day operations in continuously developed and deployed systems (host and app)
- periodical training of personnel on general IT security and PCI DSS related topics

## Benefits:
- Motivating salary;
- Opportunity to grow with an innovative FinTech start-up
- Excellent work conditions and flexible working hours
- A professional and friendly team

Please submit your application by email: [cv@travelunion.eu](mailto:cv@travelunion.eu)

By sending your CV, you agree to UAB "Travel Union" [Candidate Policy Notice](https://mytu.lt/teisine-informacija?document=CP).
